# FluentValidation

- Create one validator per request DTO, named `<Dto>Validator`
- Register validators with `AddFluentValidationAutoValidation()` in `Program.cs` — don't manually call `.Validate()` in controllers
- Keep validation rules declarative; use `.WithMessage()` for user-facing errors
- Use `.MustAsync()` for rules that require DB lookups

## Example: basic validator for a ToDo request
```csharp
// ✅ Clean validator — controller stays thin
public class CreateToDoRequestValidator : AbstractValidator<CreateToDoRequest>
{
    public CreateToDoRequestValidator()
    {
        RuleFor(x => x.Description)
            .NotEmpty().WithMessage("Description is required.")
            .MaximumLength(500).WithMessage("Description must be 500 characters or fewer.");

        RuleFor(x => x.DueDate)
            .GreaterThanOrEqualTo(DateOnly.FromDateTime(DateTime.Today))
            .When(x => x.DueDate.HasValue)
            .WithMessage("Due date cannot be in the past.");
    }
}

// ❌ Don't validate manually in the controller
if (string.IsNullOrEmpty(request.Description)) return BadRequest("...");
```

## Example: async rule checking uniqueness
```csharp
// ✅ Use MustAsync for DB-dependent rules
RuleFor(x => x.Description)
    .MustAsync(async (desc, ct) =>
        !await db.ToDos.AnyAsync(t => t.Description == desc, ct))
    .WithMessage("A ToDo with that description already exists.");
```
